246
26:28.830 --> 26:34.380
So what we can do is to apply V dagger to whatever state we
obtained from our circuit.

247
26:34.380 --> 26:43.890
And then if we perform a
standard basis measurement, we'll get the number Y
that we're looking for, expressed as a string
of length two in binary.

248
26:43.890 --> 26:49.500
Before we go any further, let's talk a bit more
about the unitary matrix V.

249
26:49.500 --> 26:53.790
This is a special matrix and
you may have seen it before.

250
26:53.790 --> 27:01.440
It's the matrix associated
with a linear operation on four dimensional vectors known as the discrete Fourier transform.

251
27:01.440 --> 27:10.230
To be more precise, the discrete Fourier transform can be defined for any
positive integer dimension, and we'll take a look at it
in general in a few moments.

252
27:10.230 --> 27:15.900
And this is what it
looks like specifically when the dimension is equal to four.

253
27:15.900 --> 27:19.950
We can think about the
discrete Fourier transform in different ways.

254
27:19.950 --> 27:28.245
We can think about it purely abstractly as a linear mapping on vectors that can be represented by a matrix.

255
27:28.245 --> 27:34.710
And we can also think about
it as a computational problem where we're given a vector, and we want to compute the result

256
27:34.710 --> 27:39.630
of applying this linear mapping.

257
27:39.630 --> 27:46.560
That turns out to be an incredibly important
computational problem, and there's a highly efficient algorithm for performing that computation

258
27:46.560 --> 27:50.100
known as the fasts Fourier transform.

259
27:50.100 --> 27:57.990
In fact, this is such an important problem in signal processing for example, that the fasts Fourier
transform is considered by many

260
27:57.990 --> 28:03.030
to be one of the most important and consequential
algorithms ever discovered.

261
28:03.030 --> 28:10.410
We can also think about the
discrete Fourier transform as a unitary quantum operation that can be applied to
a quantum state vector.

262
28:10.410 --> 28:18.000
And when we think about it in that way, we call it the quantum Fourier
transform, or QFT for short.

263
28:18.000 --> 28:24.810
Mathematically speaking, it's essentially the same thing as the discrete Fourier transform, but we call it the
quantum Fourier transform

264
28:24.810 --> 28:30.390
just to clarify that it's an operation being applied to a quantum state vector.

265
28:30.390 --> 28:36.810
So let's change the name of our matrix, from V to QFT four to reflect the fact

266
28:36.810 --> 28:43.410
that the operation that we've come up with is in fact the quantum Fourier transform.

267
28:43.410 --> 28:49.920
So here's the complete circuit for learning the value of Y when we're promised that
theta equals Y over four

268
28:49.920 --> 28:53.640
for Y being zero, one, two, or three.

269
28:53.640 --> 29:00.720
And just to make sure it's clear, we're applying the inverse of
the quantum Fourier transform, or in other words QFT four dagger

270
29:00.720 --> 29:10.200
to map one of the four possible states back to the standard basis state, cat Y, so that we can recover Y by measuring.

271
29:10.200 --> 29:17.100
So that's the circuit we
get from thinking about the promised version of the
phase estimation problem, where we're promised that theta

272
29:17.100 --> 29:23.130
is zero, one quarter, one
half, or three quarters, but there's nothing that prevents us

273
29:23.130 --> 29:28.620
from running this circuit for
an arbitrary value of theta.

274
29:28.620 --> 29:35.130
And if we do that, here
are the probabilities for the four possible
outcomes that we obtain.

275
29:35.130 --> 29:43.920
Each of the four possible
values for Y has its own color, and the plot tells us
what the probabilities are for each one as a function of theta.

276
29:43.920 --> 29:50.280
So for instance, if theta
is equal to three quarters, we'll get the outcome
three with probability one,

277
29:50.280 --> 29:58.530
well the probabilities for the other three outcomes are all zero as we already know from thinking about the promise version of the problem.

278
29:58.530 --> 30:06.240
If theta is close to three quarters but not exactly three quarters, there will be some non-zero probability associated with the other outcomes,

279
30:06.240 --> 30:10.110
but we'll still get the outcome
three with high probability.

280
30:10.110 --> 30:17.550
So even though theta may
not be equal to Y over four, we can still think
about the outcome we get from the measurements divided by four

281
30:17.550 --> 30:21.630
as being a guess or an
approximation for theta.

282
30:21.630 --> 30:27.570
The guess may be wrong, but nevertheless it is
providing us with information.

283
30:27.570 --> 30:36.060
And one thing that we
can learn from the plot is that best approximations always have the highest
probabilities associated with them.

284
30:36.060 --> 30:43.452
When I say best approximation, I mean whatever value of Y over four is closest to the true value of theta,

285
30:43.452 --> 30:51.840
in the modular one sense. The worst possible case is that theta is exactly halfway between
two values of Y over four.

286
30:51.840 --> 30:59.850
For example, if theta is equal
to three eighths or 0.375, in this case we see
that the approximations

287
30:59.850 --> 31:03.930
one quarter and two quarters
or one half are equally good.

288
31:03.930 --> 31:08.854
So in this particular
case there are actually two best approximations rather than one.

289
31:08.854 --> 31:12.360
And we're equally likely to get the outcome one
and the outcome two.

290
31:12.360 --> 31:20.400
The other two outcomes zero and three, which don't give very good
approximations to theta when we divide by four, actually do appear with some probability

291
31:20.400 --> 31:24.840
which appears to be just
under 10% in both cases.

292
31:24.840 --> 31:30.180
So this procedure isn't perfect, but it does provide us with information.

293
31:30.180 --> 31:36.390
And it's noteworthy that
regardless of theta, we're always guaranteed to draw either the best approximation

294
31:36.390 --> 31:44.250
or one of the two best approximations when there's a tie, with probability that
appears to be just above 40%.

